article.description:
Paul Pierce scored 28 points and Antoine
Walker added 17, leading the Boston Celtics to a 100-94 victory
over Philadelphia.
article.headline: Rogers, Delk help Boston's cause as Iverson goes cold

images.name: Pierce_Paul 020304 vtop
images.caption: Paul Pierce, left, averaged 27 ppg against Philly this season.

article.linkText: Newcomers finally help Celtics find groove
article.story:
PHILADELPHIA (AP) -- This was why the Boston Celtics acquired Rodney Rogers and Tony Delk. Paul Pierce scored 28 points, Rogers had 15 and Delk added 12, leading the Celtics to a 100-94 victory over the Philadelphia 76ers on Monday night. Boston had lost four in a row since trading Joe Johnson, Milt Palacio and a first-round draft choice this year to Phoenix for Delk and Rogers. "We've been trying to get more comfortable," Rogers said. "This was a good one for us." Allen Iverson, coming off consecutive 40-point performances, scored 28, but missed 22 of his 30 shots. The Sixers, who had won three in a row, missed an opportunity to move into a three-way tie with Boston and Orlando for second place in the Atlantic Division and the No. 4 spot in the Eastern Conference. "We really wanted this game a lot," Iverson said. "It's a setback. We have to get back on track Wednesday." After squandering a nine-point lead in the third quarter, Philadelphia scored six in a row to close to 87-86 with 4:33 left. But Rogers made a putback, got fouled and hit the free throw to extend Boston's lead to 90-86. A three-point play by Eric Snow cut it to 91-89 with 2:59 left, but Walter McCarty scored on a driving layup and put back a miss by Pierce to make it 95-89 with 1:51 left. The Sixers didn't get closer than four the rest of the way. "Rodney Rogers gave us a big lift off the bench and Delk did a real good job playing the point," Celtics coach Jim O'Brien said. "This was a good win for us. We played with a lot of intensity." Rogers scored nine points in the fourth quarter, including two 3-pointers. He also had two key offensive rebounds. "It's great to be in there with the game on the line," Rogers said. "I had some good looks on the 3s." Pierce missed six of his first seven shots and was 3-for-12 in the first half, but scored 11 points in the fourth. Antoine Walker had 17 points. Snow and Derrick Coleman each had 16 for Philadelphia. But Matt Harpring shot 2-for-11 and Dikembe Mutombo only took three shots, got into foul trouble and wasn't on the court late in the game because the Sixers went to a quicker lineup to counter Boston's smaller lineup. "I don't think our shot selection was great," Sixers coach Larry Brown said. "You can't overcome 8-for-30 and 2-for-11." The Sixers used a 20-3 run to erase a nine-point deficit in the third quarter and take their first lead since the opening minutes. Iverson, who missed eight of his first nine shots and 11 of 13 in the first half, hit his first three shots in the third quarter, and had 10 points during the run. "They were shadowing me," he said. "When I got the ball, there was always another man standing there zoning up with Walker. Any time I got by my man, there was always another one there." Game notes
Sixers guard Aaron McKie missed the game with a sprained left ankle. He has sat out 14 of the team's last 17 games. ... Celtics center Tony Battie didn't play because of a right leg injury. ... It was Pajama Party night at the First Union Center. The 10 fans with the best pajamas won an overnight stay at a downtown hotel. ... Boston snapped an eight-game losing streak against the Sixers, including two 16-point defeats this season. ... Iverson was 9-for-9 from the foul line after hitting all 10 of his free throws Sunday.
